  "prompt": "What are some good examples of software architectural debt?",
  "response": "Here are several good examples of software architectural debt:\n\n1. Monolithic Architecture\n- Single, tightly-coupled codebase\n- Difficult to scale and modify\n- Limited technology stack flexibility\n- High deployment complexity\n\n2. Technical Debt in Microservices\n- Poorly defined service boundaries\n- Excessive inter-service dependencies\n- Inconsistent communication protocols\n- Complex service orchestration\n\n3. Legacy System Integration\n- Outdated technology stacks\n- Complex integration points\n- High maintenance overhead\n- Limited scalability\n\n4. Database Design Issues\n- Normalized database with performance bottlenecks\n- Lack of proper indexing\n- Complex query structures\n- Inefficient data access patterns\n\n5. Performance Anti-Patterns\n- N+1 query problems\n- Inefficient caching strategies\n- Synchronous processing in distributed systems\n- Lack of horizontal scaling considerations\n\n6. Security Design Flaws\n- Improper authentication mechanisms\n- Monolithic security implementations\n- Centralized authorization models\n- Insufficient encryption strategies\n\n7. Configuration Management\n- Hard-coded configurations\n- Limited environment flexibility\n- Complex deployment processes\n- Manual configuration management\n\n8. Code Coupling\n- Tight module interdependencies\n- High cyclomatic complexity\n- Difficult refactoring\n- Limited modular design\n\n9. State Management\n- Complex global state handling\n- Inconsistent data synchronization\n- Lack of proper state isolation\n- Inefficient event propagation\n\n10. Scalability Limitations\n- Single-threaded architectures\n- Limited horizontal scaling capabilities\n- Resource-intensive processing\n- Poor load balancing design\n\nThese examples highlight common architectural challenges that can accumulate technical debt over time.",
